-- Gilead, Sperian, Skadden, Lockheed, Tata-Greenpeace: Intellectual Property
-- Victoria Slind-Flor
-- 2010-07-22T11:01:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-22/gilead-sperian-skadden-lockheed-tata-greenpeace-intellectual-property.html

          
          
             Gilead Sciences Inc. ,  Merck & Co. 
and  Johnson & Johnson  are in talks to license their patented
AIDS treatments to generic-drug makers in developing nations, a
Geneva-based health funding agency said.  
 The three companies have had conversations with the agency,
known as  Unitaid , about making the licenses available through a
so-called patent pool, said Ellen ‘t Hoen, Unitaid’s senior
adviser on intellectual property.  
 The pool would be a central point through which companies
such as Gilead could allow makers of copycat pills to market the
drugs in poorer nations. It would help coordinate agreements on
combination pills that include drugs made by different
companies, ‘t Hoen said. The initiative would be the first pool
for HIV medicines, following the success of similar programs for
agriculture and information technology, Unitaid said.  
 “We’re talking about the how rather than the whether” the
companies will participate, ‘t Hoen said in an interview at the
 International AIDS Conference  in Vienna yesterday.  
 The pool “is an important initiative and Gilead is
actively participating in discussions about how this kind of
innovative approach will move forward,” Cara Miller, a
spokeswoman for the Foster City, California-based drugmaker,
said in an e-mail.  
 A spokesman for Merck of Whitehouse Station, New Jersey,
and a spokeswoman for New Brunswick, New Jersey-based Johnson &
Johnson didn’t immediately respond to e-mails seeking comment.  
 GlaxoSmithKline Plc said last week that it will give
licenses to generic-drug makers in poor countries to produce the
HIV medicines it makes in a joint venture with  Pfizer Inc.  The
policy extends to 69 of the world’s least developed countries,
where 80 percent of all people with HIV live, the London-based
drugmaker said.  
 A Glaxo spokeswoman didn’t immediately respond to an e-mail
seeking comment today on Unitaid’s patent pool.  
 Research on HIV drugs made by Gilead, Pfizer, Glaxo, Merck,
Johnson & Johnson, Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. and Boehringer
Ingelheim GmbH are to be presented at the AIDS conference today.  
 Sperian Sued, Accused of Infringing Safety Glasses Patent  
 Sperian Protection , a French maker of safety equipment, was
sued for patent infringement by a Massachusetts-based
manufacturer of glasses and other eyewear products.  
 Hilsinger Co. claims products made and sold by Sperian
infringe a patent for glasses with removable lenses. Hilsinger’s
patent 6,227,665, which was issued in May 2001, is for sport
glasses with a plastic frame and lens-receiving sections.  
 Hilsinger asked the court to order all Sperian units to
quit selling the allegedly infringing products and to remove
them from the Internet, catalogs and retail stores. It also
seeks a recall -- including from customers -- of all infringing
products.  
 The Plainville, Massachusetts-based company requested
awards of litigation costs, attorney fees and money damages and
asked that the damages be tripled to punish Sperian for what
Hilsinger says is willful infringement.  
 Hilsinger is represented by  Christine K. Bush ,  Craig M.
Scott  and  Thomas Connolly  of  Scott Bush Ltd.  of Providence,
Rhode Island.  
 The case is Hilsinger Co. v. Sperian Eye & Face Protection
Inc., 1:10-cv-00302, ML-LDA, U.S. District Court, District of
Rhode Island (Providence).  
 Mattel Gets Patent for Doll With Moveable, Alterable Features  
 Mattel Inc. , the world’s biggest toymaker, received a
patent for a doll with features that can be altered.  
 Patent 7,744,442, one of  5,072 U.S. patents  issued July 20,
covers a doll with mechanisms that can alter its cheek, eye
position and mouth opening by moving levers. The doll’s face
could also be changed by manipulating its torso, such as
pressing the doll’s stomach to make it smile.  
 According to the patent, the mechanisms can be engaged if
the doll is upright or in a laid-back position, such as being
cradled in the user’s arms. The doll can also contain a sound
generator that will output various sounds depending on how the
face is altered.  
 Mattel presently offers “ Little Mommy Baby Ah-Choo ,” a
doll that sneezes when its stomach is squeezed.  
 El Segundo, California-based Mattel applied for the patent
in June 2008 with the assistance of  Kolisch Hartwell PC  of
Portland, Oregon.  
