 Copyright  
 Skadden Added as Defendant in Baseball-Song Infringement Suit  
 A Boston-based musician whose original copyright-
infringement case against  Time Warner Inc. , Turner Broadcasting
System and Major League Baseball was tossed out in August, re-
filed the case and added a New York law firm to the list of
defendants.  
 Samuel Bartley Steele filed a copyright-infringement suit
in federal court in Boston in October 2008, claiming his song
“Man I Love This Town” was infringed by a commercial for Major
League Baseball. The allegedly offending commercial used Bon
Jovi’s “I Love This Town” as a sound track.  
 Judge Nathaniel Gorton, in his Aug. 19 ruling, said the two
songs “display little lyrical similarity” and the “common
expressions and cliches” in Steel’s songs weren’t protected by
copyright law. Steele filed an appeal in November.  
 He filed his new complaint in Boston federal court July 20
and added New York’s  Skadden Arps Slate Meagher & Flom LLP  as a
defendant. Steele said that Skadden, which represented the
defendants in the original case, has failed to provide him, his
lawyers or the appeals court “a copy of the unaltered true and
correct version” of the commercial he says infringed.  
 He also claimed the firm, together with the other
defendants, intentionally removed copyright-management
information from the commercial.  
 Steele is represented by Christopher A.D. Hunt from the
Hunt Law Firm LLC of Hopedale, Massachusetts.  
 The new case is Steele v. Bongiovi, 1:10-cv-11218, U.S.
District Court, District of Massachusetts (Boston). The initial
case is Steele v. Turner Broadcasting System Inc., 1:08-cv-
11727-NMG, U.S. District Court, District of Massachusetts
(Boston). The appeal is Steele v. Turner Broadcasting System,
09-2571, 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals (Boston).  
