 Trademark  
 Lochkeed Warns Fly-Rod Maker Not to Use ‘Skunk Works’ Mark  
 Lockheed Martin Corp. , the world’s largest defense
contractor, has told a maker of bamboo rods used for fly-fishing
that his website infringes the company’s trademark.  
 Sections of a letter from counsel for Lockheed are posted
on the Trout Underground blog site. In the letter, sent by  Lynne
Boisineau  of Chicago’s  McDermott Will & Emery , the fishing-rod
maker was told his choice of skunkworksflyrods.com as a domain
name  “is in bad faith and is an attempt to profit off the
goodwill of the Skunk Works trademark” and the misdirect the
“unwitting public” away from the defense contractor’s official
 Skunk Works website .  
 The term had its origins in a “ L’il Abner ” comic strip by
the late  Al Capp , who used “skonk works” as a name for an
illegal still in the swampy backwoods of Dogpatch, an imaginary
town.  
 According to the database of the U.S. Patent and Trademark
Office, Lockheed first registered “skunk works” as a trademark
in July 1981. The mark is registered for use with “engineering
technical consulting, and advisory services with respect to
designing, building, equipping, and testing commercial and
military aircraft and related equipment.”  
 In November 2001 Lockheed added another registration for
the mark, to be used with games, sporting articles and stuffed
animals.  
 The conflict with the fishing-gear maker isn’t the first
time Lockheed has tried to keep others from using the mark. In
the U.K., the Bethesda, Maryland-based company tried to block a
company with the “in the Leaf we trust” motto from using
www.ukskunkworks.co.uk from selling marijuana seeds and
paraphernalia.  
 In that appeal, U.K. Skunkworks Ltd. claimed Lockheed “has
used its size, resources and financial position to employ
“bullyboy tactics” against a small company.  
 The  Internet registry panel for .UK domain names  said in an
 April 2007 decision  that the U.K. company was carrying on a
“genuine business,” and noted that “skunk” is sometimes used
for a particular strain of cannabis.  
 The fear of negative associations could cut both ways, the
panel said, noting that while the defense contractor may not
want people to assume a connection with a marijuana-related
business, “many people have as little a wish to be associated
with military aircraft” as Lockheed does with illegal drug use.
“The risk of ‘contamination by association’ therefore seems
low,” the panel said.  
 Additionally, the panel noted that in Bill Gates’
autobiography, he implemented a skunkworks at  Microsoft Corp. 
“Through a social process, the term ‘skunk works’ has clearly
passed into general language,” the panel said, ruling that the
U.K. company’s domain name “be left undisturbed.”  
 Tata Sues Greenpeace, Says ‘Turtle v. Tata’ Infringes Marks  
 Tata Sons Ltd., the holding company for India’s Tata Group,
sued Greenpeace for trademark infringement in the Delhi High
Court, India’s Financial Express  reported .  
 The suit is related to Greenpeace’s online game  Turtle v.
Tata , in which colored balls allegedly bearing Tata’s trademark
without authorization annihilate a sea turtle, according to the
Financial Express.  
 Amsterdam-based  Greenpeace International , an environmental
advocacy group, created the game to focus public attention on a
deepwater port Tata is constructing at Orissa, India, that the
group says endangers Olive Ridley Sea Turtles, the Financial
Express reported.  
 Tata, which is represented by  Anand & Andand  of New Delhi,
claims the game infringes and makes disparaging and libelous
references to the company, according to the newspaper.  
 Ozzy Osbourne , Tony Iommi Settle Black Sabbath Name Dispute  
 A trademark dispute over ownership of the Black Sabbath
band name has been settled, according to court filings.  
 John “Ozzy” Osbourne sued  Anthony Iommi  in federal court
in Manhattan in May 2009 for trademark infringement. Osbourne
asked the court to declare that he was co-owner of the mark, and
for an award of the profits Iommi received from his alleged
infringement.  
 Iommi was also a founding member of Black Sabbath.  
 Terms of the settlement weren’t disclosed in court filings.
According to court documents, each party will pay its own
litigation costs and attorney fees.  
 Osbourne is represented by  Mimi Kristin Rupp  and  Howard
Jeffrey Shire  of New York’s  Kenyon & Kenyon LLP . Iommi was
represented by  Amin S. Kassam  and  Joseph Vecchione DeMarco  of
New York’s  DeVore & DeMarco LLP .  
 The case is John Osbourne v. Anthony Iommi, 1:09-cv-
0949747-JGK, U.S. District Court, Southern District of New York
(Manhattan).  
